2026-04-16 12:38:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['sensor-operated relay contacts in ambient sensor (control) module'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU provides a solid ~12 V, and this same voltage appears at the input of the ambient sensor module with correct polarity. However, at the relay inside the control module there is ~11.99 V on the input side and only ~0.36 V on the output side, so roughly the entire supply is dropping across the relay contacts while the load side sits at about 0.36 V. This is exactly the behavior of a failed (high-resistance) relay contact rather than one that is being periodically opened and closed. The lamp sees only ~0.36 V and therefore should actually be very dim or off, independent of the timing potentiometer. Since the timing potentiometer sweep did not affect the behavior and the control module output remains at ~0.36 V, the most plausible root cause is that the relay contacts inside the ambient sensor/control module are damaged/oxidized or otherwise not closing properly. Replacing or repairing the sensor-operated relay in the control module should restore a low-resistance connection and allow the full 12 V to reach the load module, eliminating the observed malfunction.'
