2026-04-16 12:39:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module ground/negative output wiring', 'ambient sensor (control) module negative output terminal connection to Control Input Cable (−)', 'internal PCB trace or jumper from relay / circuitry return to the output − terminal'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show the +12 V path from the power‑supply module through the relay contacts to the control module output + terminal and up to the load module is essentially ideal (milliohm continuity, no series elements). Yet at the control module output we only see about +0.36 V relative to the negative output, while the control module input sees the full 11.99 V. This implies that the 0 V reference at the control output is not the same node as the 0 V at the control input – i.e., the negative/ground side of the output pair is not actually connected to the supply negative.\n\nWith the relay path confirmed good and the relay contacts already disproved as faulty, the only remaining way to obtain ~0.36 V at the output while having 11.99 V present on the upstream side is for the output negative terminal (and/or its internal connection in the ambient sensor module) to be open, miswired, or connected through a very high resistance to the true 0 V node. In that case, the measuring instrument and the load form a leakage path that biases the nominal + output to a small residual voltage (~0.36 V) instead of 12 V, even though the + line from the power supply itself is healthy.\n\nTherefore the most probable fault is in the ground/negative wiring of the ambient sensor (control) module – specifically the internal connection from the module’s circuit/common 0 V (which is correctly tied to the Control Input Cable (−)) to the Control Output Cable (−). This could be a missing or broken PCB trace, a mis‑soldered or unconnected output − terminal, or a wiring error in that branch. Repairing/restoring this negative output connection should restore a full 12 V differential at the control output and eliminate the abnormal behavior at the load.'
