2026-04-16 12:40:18 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module relay coil return wiring / reference node (connection from relay coil negative pin to Control Input Cable (−) / module ground)', 'any unintended series element or miswire placing the relay coil negative node in series with the relay contact output path inside the ambient sensor (control) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show:\n- PSU output and control module input: ~11.99 V.\n- Relay common contact: ~11.99 V.\n- Relay NO contact, control output +, and all the way into the load input +: ~0.36 V.\n- Relay coil positive: ~11.99 V; coil negative: ~0.36 V, giving ~11.63 V across the coil.\nThus the same node (~0.36 V) is simultaneously acting as (a) the relay contact output node and (b) the relay coil return node, instead of being tied solidly to the 0 V reference.\nElectrically this can only happen if there is a wiring / PCB error at the coil’s negative side or its reference node, such that the relay coil return is not properly connected to the module’s 0 V (Control Input Cable −), and is instead connected into the switched output path or through an unintended series element. That makes the load, the relay contacts, and the coil form a series chain between +12 V and the true 0 V; the coil then drops about 11.6 V and the load/output node floats at ~0.36 V. The relay contacts themselves continuity‑test correctly when unpowered, explaining the previous continuity result, but under operation they sit at this intermediate potential.\nTherefore the root cause is not bad contacts but a fault in the relay coil return / ground reference wiring or layout inside the ambient sensor (control) module, likely a misrouted PCB trace, wrong jumper, or wrong connection that ties the coil negative node into the contact output path rather than to the proper 0 V node. Reworking that connection to the correct ground / negative input should restore full 12 V at the relay NO contact and eliminate the abnormal low output and flicker.'
