2026-04-16 12:40:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=["relay contact wiring / PCB connection between relay common pin and relay NO pin inside ambient sensor (control) module, specifically the swapped or mis-assigned pins such that the measured 'common' node is actually a coil node at ~12 V and the measured 'NO' node is actually tied to the coil return at ~0.36 V, causing the load to be fed from the relay coil circuit instead of the true contact pair"] hypothesis_explanation="All voltage measurements show a consistent ~11.99 V at the control module input + referenced to the true negative. The relay coil has ~11.63 V across it, with its positive side at ~11.99 V and its negative side at ~0.36 V relative to the true negative. The control output +, which should be on the NO contact of the relay, is also at ~0.36 V. Thus the output node is sitting at the relay coil negative potential rather than at the contact pair that should short directly from input + to output + when energized.\n\nContinuity testing with power off reported ~0 Ω from Control Input Cable (+) through the relay to Control Output Cable (+), which would be consistent with the technician probing across a path that appears continuous at DC (via internal miswiring or shared pins) but is not the intended contact pair under live operation. With power on, however, the detailed node measurements show that the drop from ~12 V to ~0.36 V occurs exactly between the node identified as the relay 'common' (11.99 V) and the node identified as relay 'NO' (0.36 V). This is the same potential difference as across the coil, strongly indicating that the contact side being probed as NO is actually tied into the coil return network, not to the true contact output.\n\nThe lamp’s 20‑second brief outages are consistent with the control circuit modulating or refreshing the coil drive; because the load is incorrectly connected into the coil path, any small variations in drive or contact behavior manifest as the lamp briefly extinguishing even though the main supply remains good. The repeated failed hypotheses that the contacts themselves, the negative output wiring, or the coil return path are individually faulty point instead toward an internal misassignment of relay pins or PCB track—effectively a configuration/wiring fault inside the control module where the relay contact pins are wired to the wrong pads or traces.\n\nTherefore the most plausible root cause is that the relay contact wiring/PCB layout inside the ambient sensor (control) module is miswired or its common/NO pins are swapped so that the load output is connected to the relay coil return node (~0.36 V) rather than to the true switched contact that should carry the full 12 V from the input when energized."
