2026-04-16 12:40:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module relay device (entire relay component, including internal contact mechanism and coil–contact isolation)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage and continuity tests indicate: (1) the PSU delivers a solid 12 V; (2) the control module input sees the same 12 V with correct polarity; (3) the relay coil is driven with ~11.6–12 V continuously when the lamp should be on; (4) with power removed, the PCB traces from input + → relay common → relay NO → output + measure essentially 0 Ω (0.01–0.10 Ω) and no unintended series resistance or mis‑wiring is detected; yet (5) under power, the node labeled relay common remains at ~11.99 V while the node labeled relay NO, the control output +, and all downstream points sit at ~0.36 V, meaning ~11.6 V is dropped across what should be a closed relay contact. The negative rail is solid at ~0 V, and previous hypotheses about miswired returns or swapped pins have been disproved by unsuccessful repair attempts.\n\nThe only remaining consistent explanation is that the relay component itself is internally defective: its contact set does not form a low‑resistance metallic connection when the energized coil pulls in. Instead, the contacts behave as a high‑resistance path (or partially welded / contaminated interface) that passes only a small leakage current, creating the observed 11.6 V drop across the closed contact pair and leaving only ~0.36 V at the load. The continuity test with power off would still show near‑zero ohms if the contacts mechanically touch or if test current burns through oxide momentarily, but under real load the effective resistance rises dramatically, producing the large voltage drop.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a faulty relay device in the ambient sensor (control) module, and the correct repair is to replace the entire relay component rather than its external wiring or PCB connections.'
