2026-04-16 12:41:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module internal light-sensor / comparator circuit causing periodic dropout of relay drive around every 20 s'] hypothesis_explanation='All wiring, relay contacts, relay device, coil return, PCB traces, and module interconnections have been verified good; the PSU output is a solid 12 V. Yet the measured behavior is that the control-module output sits at ~0.36 V while the relay coil is driven with about 11.6 V across it (11.99 V and 0.36 V on its pins). This matches a design where the coil negative node is not at true ground but is intentionally referenced to the load side or an internal sensing node, so that the coil current and load current share part of the same path. The 0.36 V found at the output and at the coil negative pin is therefore not due to a bad connection or bad relay but is the normal node potential of that reference network. \n\nGiven that the relay and its connections are confirmed healthy yet the lamp still periodically turns off for about 0.5 s every ~20 s, the only remaining plausible cause is that the ambient-light sensor and its associated comparator/timing circuitry are intermittently removing or modulating the drive to the relay coil. The ~20 s period corresponds well to a timing network governed by the timing potentiometer and RC components; the fact that sweeping the timing pot produced no reported permanent change suggests that the fault lies in the sensor/comparator IC or its surrounding passive components (e.g., a leaky capacitor, faulty op-amp/comparator, or misbiased transistor) that create an unintended oscillation or threshold chatter near the setpoint. This would briefly de-energize the relay, causing the lamp to drop out, yet when measured in steady-state the coil still shows near-normal voltage as the meter averages the behavior.\n\nTherefore the root cause is localized to the internal light-sensor/comparator/timing circuit inside the ambient sensor (control) module, which is malfunctioning and periodically cutting or modulating the relay drive, not in the relay or wiring themselves. Repair/replace that internal control circuit (sensor IC, comparator/op-amp, or its timing network) within the control module.'
