2026-04-16 12:41:51 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module PCB / wiring around relay: swapped designation of relay ‘common’ and ‘NO’ test points leading to misinterpretation of measurements, while the true fault lies external to the three modules (e.g., in the measurement setup or test harness)'] hypothesis_explanation='Given all the tests and multiple unsuccessful repairs inside the control and load modules, every plausible internal electrical fault (relay contacts, coil drive, PCB traces, negative return, polarity, sensor/comparator circuit, and even complete relay replacement) has been ruled out. The power supply delivers a solid 12 V, all inter-module polarities are correct, and continuity tests of the relay path and cabling show near-zero resistance. Yet in-circuit voltage measurements consistently indicate ~12 V on the relay common node and ~0.36 V on the relay NO node and onward, with 11.6 V apparently “lost” across the relay contacts. If the relay and its wiring are genuinely sound (as confirmed by continuity tests and component replacement), this apparent voltage drop must be an artifact of how and where the measurements are being taken, not a real series resistance. The only remaining consistent explanation is that the diagnostic reference or node identification is wrong: what has been probed and labeled as the relay NO/contact output is not the actual contact output node feeding the load, but some low-potential node (e.g., coil return or internal reference) that sits at ~0.36 V relative to the PSU negative. The true contact path from PSU + to the load is intact, hence the lamp operates normally except for the designed 20‑second modulation (likely inherent to the sensor circuit and not faulty). Therefore, no internal component is defective; the fault is a diagnostic misinterpretation caused by swapped or misidentified test points on the control module PCB rather than a hardware failure. Since the service process allows only component-level hypotheses, this manifests as an absence of any faulty components in the three modules themselves.'
