2026-04-16 12:42:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor (control) module output + measurement reference / test setup (meter negative lead not actually on the true circuit 0 V but on the relay‑coil return node at ≈0.36 V, or equivalent mis-referenced ground point)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical tests on the three modules are self‑consistent if the system circuitry itself is healthy, and the only anomaly is that every in‑circuit DC voltage measurement downstream of the control module reads about 0.36 V above “0 V,” while continuity tests show solid low‑ohm connections and the lamp and relay are off.\n\nKey facts:\n- PSU output is a solid ~12 V and its LED works; inter‑module polarities and cabling are correct.\n- The control relay contacts show ~0 Ω continuity from PSU + through the relay to the load +, and continuity of the − path is good; there is no unexpected series resistance.\n- With power applied, the relay coil sees about 11.63 V (11.99 V vs 0.36 V on its pins), consistent with it being fully driven.\n- Yet, the same two physical relay contact nodes previously measured ~11.99 V and ~0.36 V, suggesting an 11.6 V drop across a path that ohm‑meters as a short. That is impossible for the same node pair under correct measurement referencing.\n- The load module input and the node after its series diode also both sit at ~0.36 V relative to the indicated “0 V”, and stay there (apart from the earlier reported blinking), which is exactly what you’d read if your reference (‘ground’) lead were actually clamped to an internal node that is floating ~0.36 V above the true battery negative.\n- Continuity and wiring tests have repeatedly ruled out internal miswirings, swapped cables, bad grounds, or faulty relay/driver circuitry; several complete relay replacements had no effect.\n\nThe only way to reconcile: the 0.36 V node used as the negative reference in the voltage tests is not the true system ground but the relay‑coil return (or an equivalent node that is in series with the rest of the circuit). When the meter’s black lead is placed on this node, every other node that is actually at battery negative appears at ~−0.36 V (clipped to 0 V by meter), and the battery + appears at about 12 V − 0.36 V ≈ 11.6 V relative to that mistaken reference, creating the illusion of an 11.6 V drop across good relay contacts.\n\nTherefore the real fault is not in any of the modules but in how the voltage measurements are being referenced—specifically, the measurement setup is repeatedly using the relay‑coil return node (≈0.36 V above true ground) instead of the actual Control Input Cable (−)/battery negative as the reference. Once the meter negative is correctly attached to the true 0 V node, the anomalous 0.36 V readings and apparent 11.6 V drop across good relay contacts will disappear, and the true cause of the original lamp blinking (likely normal sensor behavior or a separate intermittent issue) can be evaluated without this measurement artifact.'
