2026-04-16 12:42:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['battery in power supply module (12 V lithium cell)'] hypothesis_explanation='All wiring, relay contacts, polarity, and module interconnections have been verified good. Continuity from PSU + through the closed relay contacts to the load input + is essentially 0 Ω, and the relay is confirmed to close solidly. Yet, with the system under load, only about 0.36 V appears at the control output and load input, and this same ~0.36 V node also appears at the relay coil negative side, indicating a common low‑voltage rail. The PSU output was measured at ~11.99 V with the modules connected, but subsequent observations show both the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp are not lit at all, even though the PSU indicator LED (a very light load) is on. This is consistent with a battery that has a very high internal resistance or is nearly depleted: it can maintain 12 V when only the small PSU LED load is present (or when measured with a high‑impedance meter), but when the relay coil and lamp circuit are engaged it collapses so that the whole powered circuitry (relay coil negative, output +, load input, etc.) floats near a few hundred millivolts above the true negative terminal. The measured ~11.6 V drop across what were thought to be the relay contacts is actually the collapse of the supply between the true battery positive (still near 12 V) and the sagged circuit node at ~0.36 V, not a contact problem. Replacing the 12 V battery in the power supply module with a known‑good cell should restore a solid 12 V under load and eliminate the apparent relay/contact anomalies and the lamp’s abnormal brief operation pattern.'
