2026-04-16 12:43:55 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['internal wiring / PCB layout of ambient sensor (control) module relay coil (coil pins reversed so that the node marked/used as “coil negative” is actually tied to +12 V, and the node marked as + is near ground, creating a near‑short from Control Input (+) to the relay coil negative node and only a low‑ohm (≈1.3 Ω) path from that node to Control Input (−))'] hypothesis_explanation='The latest low‑ohms measurements show that the relay coil “negative” pin is almost shorted (≈0.10 Ω) to Control Input (+) and only resistively connected (≈1.3 Ω) to Control Input (−). That is a polarity inversion at the coil node: what is assumed to be the coil return is in fact the +12 V side, and the real return is on the opposite pin, through ~1.3 Ω. This explains:\n\n• In normal operation the coil sees ~12 V across its pins (11.99 V on the true + side, ~0.36 V on the pseudo‑negative side referenced to true ground), so the relay actuates and continuity across its contacts is solid (≈0.01 Ω), matching the continuity tests.\n• Because the coil “negative” node is sitting close to +12 V (effectively tied to the supply), the rest of the circuit that references this node (including the measured contact node that appeared at 0.36 V) is biased incorrectly: the load side of the circuit is effectively driven through the coil/low‑ohm network instead of directly from +12 V relative to true 0 V. This yields the ~0.36 V observed on the control output and load input while the PSU itself is at 11.99 V.\n• The fact that replacing the relay device and checking all obvious relay contact wiring did not fix the issue implies the fault is not in the relay component itself but in how its coil pins are wired on the PCB/netlist. A footprint/pin‑assignment error that swaps the coil pins relative to the intended schematic would produce exactly this condition (coil return tied to +12 V plane, other pin routed through a low‑value resistor to ground and into the contact/output network).\n\nTherefore the root cause is a design/fabrication error in the control module’s PCB/coil wiring: the relay coil pins are connected backwards to the supply rails, effectively shorting the coil “negative” to +12 V and making the measured node at ~0.36 V a mis‑biased reference rather than the intended ground. Correcting the PCB or rewiring those coil connections to place the coil truly between +12 V and 0 V (with its return at the real ground node) should restore a proper 12 V at the control output and eliminate the abnormal low‑voltage condition at the load.'
