description: With the modules connected and powered, place the multimeter in continuity/ohms mode and connect its probes directly across the relay’s switched contacts (relay common to relay NO). First, with power OFF, confirm that the contacts read open (infinite or very high resistance). Then power ON and let the system reach the state where the lamp should be on; again measure the resistance/continuity across the same two contacts. Verify whether the meter reports a solid closed contact (near 0 Ω / continuity tone) even while about 11.6 V DC was previously measured across these same nodes, or whether the contacts in fact remain open and the prior voltage readings were made on a different node pair. Document whether the contact pair ever closes from the standpoint of a continuity test., outcome='The continuity test across the control relay’s switched contacts repeatedly measured 0.01 Ω, matching the nominal closed-contact resistance. From the standpoint of a continuity test, this contact pair is closing solidly as expected.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=40.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor (control) module relay coil negative pin to Control Input Cable (−) reference,
description: With power applied and using the Control Input Cable (−) as the reference for the multimeter’s negative lead, directly measure the DC voltage at the relay coil negative pin and at any nearby node that is tied to it (e.g., local ground plane, return trace). Confirm whether these nodes sit at ≈0.36 V above Control Input (−) or at true 0 V. Then, with power OFF, use continuity/ohms mode between the relay coil negative pin and the Control Output Cable (−) terminal to see if they are actually the same node or if there is isolation between coil return and load return., outcome='The relay coil negative node sits at approximately 0.36 V relative to the Control Input Cable (−), not at true 0 V. The relay coil negative node and the Control Output Cable (−) are not the same node but are connected through a resistive path of about 1.4 Ω.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=75.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor (control) module relay coil negative node to Control Input Cable (+) and (−) (4‑wire resistance check),
description: With power OFF, perform a precise low‑ohms (preferably 4‑wire / Kelvin) resistance measurement from the relay coil negative pin to (a) Control Input Cable (−) and (b) Control Input Cable (+). Confirm the exact resistance values and whether there is any unintended low‑ohm path from the coil negative to the +12 V rail as well as to the 0 V rail. This will clarify if the coil negative node is intentionally biased above ground by a small resistor network or is accidentally shorted/bridged to +12 V, explaining the stable ~0.36 V offset while all hardware components test as non‑faulty., outcome='Measured resistance from the relay coil negative pin to Control Input Cable (−) is 1.30 Ω, indicating a low‑ohm resistive path.  \nMeasured resistance from the relay coil negative pin to Control Input Cable (+) is 0.10 Ω, indicating a near short.  \nPOLARITY INVERSION DETECTED: Relay coil negative is effectively shorted to Control Input Cable (+) while only resistively connected to Control Input Cable (−).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=65.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
